Oh yes, because there aren't enough GPs
It is interesting to optimise flow systems but please I think it's a less important factor than the others
All the top 3 are hard to fix, and essentially require a large amount of investment- (1) public/community health, GP, (2) need more beds, (3) need mainly more/better social care

I don't think we really need to overcomplicate flow. It is predominantly three things,
1. patients in 
2. # beds 
3. patients out 

We have increasing 1, decreasing/not enough 2 and 3. 
I think structure or character of the flow is interesting but less important in relation

This implies 'flow' is an entity which if we got right would fix the NHS, irrespective of key factors. We know whatever the system of flow, if we get >95% bed occupancy things grind to a halt  https://t.co/UWMjXIAcwO
